\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs22\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af4\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\cf0\f4\fs22\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af8\langfe2052\sl-276\slmult0\ql\sb0\sa120{\rtlch\af8\afs22 \ltrch\loch\cf18\fs22\dbch\af8\loch
Revenue is generated through a per-student weekly fee of $2 (USD), collected during school terms only. Ghana\u8217\'92s academic year comprises approximately 40 school weeks across three terms. Fee collection will leverage the existing mobile money infrastructure, with payments processed through MTN MoMo, Telecel Cash, or AT Money platforms.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af6\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb300\sa150\keepn\ltrpar\cf19\f6\fs28\b\dbch\af9\sb300\sa150{\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\fs28\b\f5\dbch\af9\loch
9.2 Subsidy & Affordability}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs22\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af4\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\cf0\f4\fs22\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af8\langfe2052\sl-276\slmult0\ql\sb0\sa120{\rtlch\af8\afs22 \ltrch\loch\cf18\fs22\dbch\af8\loch
Fees are means-tested. Students in large urban centers pay the standard $2/week rate. Students in peri-urban and rural communities receive subsidies funded by the Educational Fund (described below). The subsidy structure ensures that ability to pay never determines access to education. Subsidy determination will consider household income, geographic location, and community economic indicators.}
