11. Rollout Strategy: Ghana to Pan-Africa}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af6\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb300\sa150\keepn\ltrpar\cf19\f6\fs28\b\dbch\af9\sb300\sa150{\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\fs28\b\f5\dbch\af9\loch
11.1 Phase 1: Ghana Pilot (Months 1\u8211\'9612)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs22\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af4\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\cf0\f4\fs22\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af8\langfe2052\sl-276\slmult0\ql\sb0\sa120{\rtlch\af8\afs22 \ltrch\loch\cf18\fs22\dbch\af8\loch
Deploy to 15 schools in major urban centers. Conduct feasibility study. Validate technology, pedagogy, and financial model. Build evidence base. Secure government MoU and telecom partnerships.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af6\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb300\sa150\keepn\ltrpar\cf19\f6\fs28\b\dbch\af9\sb300\sa150{\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\fs28\b\f5\dbch\af9\loch
11.2 Phase 2: Ghana National Expansion (Months 12\u8211\'9636)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs22\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af4\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\cf0\f4\fs22\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af8\langfe2052\sl-276\slmult0\ql\sb0\sa120{\rtlch\af8\afs22 \ltrch\loch\cf18\fs22\dbch\af8\loch
Scale from 15 schools to district-wide coverage in pilot regions. Begin rollout to peri-urban and rural schools. Refine subsidy mechanisms based on pilot data. Establish the Educational Fund and independent administration. Introduce mobile phone access channels.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af6\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb300\sa150\keepn\ltrpar\cf19\f6\fs28\b\dbch\af9\sb300\sa150{\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\fs28\b\f5\dbch\af9\loch
11.3 Phase 3: Ghana Full Coverage (Months 36\u8211\'9660)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs22\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af4\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\cf0\f4\fs22\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af8\langfe2052\sl-276\slmult0\ql\sb0\sa120{\rtlch\af8\afs22 \ltrch\loch\cf18\fs22\dbch\af8\loch
Achieve nationwide coverage across all Primary, JHS, and SHS institutions. Introduce local language support (Twi, Ewe, Dagbani, Ga). Demonstrate full financial self-sufficiency. Begin sharing model documentation with target expansion countries.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af6\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb300\sa150\keepn\ltrpar\cf19\f6\fs28\b\dbch\af9\sb300\sa150{\rtlch\af9\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\fs28\b\f5\dbch\af9\loch
11.4 Phase 4: Pan-African Expansion (Months 48\u8211\'9696+)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs22\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af4\loch\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar\cf0\f4\fs22\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af8\langfe2052\sl-276\slmult0\ql\sb0\sa120{\rtlch\af8\afs22 \ltrch\loch\cf18\fs22\dbch\af8\loch
Replicate the three-party model in Anglophone West Africa (Nigeria, Sierra Leone, The Gambia). Adapt platform for East African markets (Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda). Develop Francophone content for Senegal, C\u244\'f4te d\u8217\'92Ivoire, Cameroon. Each country deployment will follow the same pilot-to-scale methodology, adapted for local curriculum, language, culture, and regulatory requirements.}
